-- ── Dagster ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Dagster is an open-source data orchestration platform for building, testing, and monitoring data and AI pipelines as declarative, asset-based DAGs.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted); Dagster+ from $120/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2018, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$~85 employees (as of 2026; now part of Prefect)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Dagster Review 2026: Pricing, Features, Prefect Merger$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Dagster is an open-source data orchestration platform for asset-based pipelines. See pricing, features, and its 2026 acquisition by Prefect.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Dagster is an open-source data orchestration platform used to build, test, deploy, and monitor data and machine learning pipelines defined as directed acyclic graphs (DAGs). It was created by Nick Schrock, formerly a co-creator of GraphQL at Facebook, who founded the company originally named Elementl in 2018 to build Dagster; the company later rebranded to Dagster Labs. Dagster Labs raised roughly $49 million across a $1.8 million seed round in 2018, a $14 million Series A in November 2021 led by Index Ventures and Sequoia Capital, and a $33 million Series B in May 2023, with additional investors including 8VC, Amplify Partners, Coatue Management, F7 Ventures, and Fathom Capital. The company is headquartered in San Francisco and, as of 2026, employed roughly 83 to 85 people. Nick Schrock has served as founder, and Pete Hunt has served as CEO. In a significant development announced on July 13, 2026, workflow orchestration competitor Prefect agreed to acquire Dagster Labs, uniting the two most widely adopted successors to Apache Airflow into a single company; Prefect stated it will continue to fully maintain and invest in both open-source Dagster and Dagster+, keep pricing unchanged, and that Schrock and Hunt would move into strategic advisor roles while roughly 40 members of the Dagster team joined Prefect.

Architecturally, Dagster's core abstraction is the software-defined asset: rather than defining pipelines purely as a sequence of tasks, Dagster encourages users to declare the data assets (tables, files, ML models, dashboards) a pipeline produces, along with their dependencies, and Dagster computes the DAG of upstream and downstream relationships automatically. This asset-based model, distinct from the more task-centric approach of Apache Airflow or the flow-centric approach of Prefect, is designed to give teams built-in data lineage, freshness tracking, and observability without extra tooling. Dagster pipelines are authored in Python and can integrate with the broader modern data stack, including dbt, Spark, Pandas, Snowflake, BigQuery, Databricks, and various cloud object stores, and Dagster increasingly markets itself for orchestrating AI and LLM workloads such as retrieval-augmented generation pipelines and agent workflows, alongside traditional ETL/ELT.

The open-source core of Dagster is released under the Apache 2.0 license and can be self-hosted for free indefinitely, covering the full DAG engine, scheduler, sensors, and local web UI. For teams that want a managed control plane, Dagster Labs sells Dagster+ (formerly Dagster Cloud), a hosted or hybrid offering that adds a managed web UI, catalog search across pipelines and assets, cost and usage tracking, role-based access control, audit logging, and uptime SLAs, while still allowing customer code to execute in the customer's own infrastructure under the hybrid deployment model, or fully in Dagster's cloud under the serverless model. Dagster+ pricing was restructured effective May 1, 2026: the Solo plan, aimed at individual users, costs $120 per month and includes an allocation of 7,500 usage credits, one user, one code location, and one deployment; the Starter plan costs $1,200 per month with 30,000 credits, up to three users, and five code locations; and an Enterprise (formerly Pro) tier is available on a custom, contact-sales basis with unlimited code locations and deployments, dedicated support, and negotiated uptime SLAs. Credits in this system are consumed based on asset materializations and op executions, and additional serverless compute is billed separately if a team uses Dagster's hosted execution rather than the free hybrid model where compute runs in the customer's own cloud account. A 30-day free trial with unlimited users is available for teams evaluating Dagster+ before committing to a paid plan.

Dagster's target users are data engineering and data platform teams, ML/AI engineering teams building agentic or RAG pipelines, and analytics engineering teams that already use dbt and want native lineage and asset tracking layered on top of their transformations. Its most direct competitors are Apache Airflow (the long-standing incumbent it was explicitly designed to improve upon), Prefect (its new corporate sibling following the 2026 acquisition, previously a rival orchestrator with a more Python-native, dynamic-workflow philosophy), and newer entrants such as Mage, Kestra, and cloud-native managed orchestration offered by Databricks Workflows and AWS Step Functions. Dagster differentiates itself primarily through its asset-centric mental model, strong local development experience, and integrated data catalog and lineage features that are opinionated defaults rather than bolt-on add-ons. Reviews on sites such as G2 and Capterra generally cite Dagster's developer experience, testability, and observability as strengths, while some users note a steeper learning curve for the asset abstraction compared to simpler task-based schedulers, and note that Dagster+ credit-based pricing can be harder to predict at scale than flat per-seat pricing.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'aef224a1-fe25-4992-8146-62c270b751d5';

