-- ── DALL-E ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$DALL-E is OpenAI's text-to-image AI model family. DALL-E 3 is being retired from ChatGPT and the API in 2026, succeeded by the GPT Image model line.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (ChatGPT); from $0.04/image (API, DALL-E 3, being phased out)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2015, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Large (OpenAI employs several thousand people globally)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Multilingual prompt support$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$DALL-E 3 in 2026: Status, Pricing, and GPT Image Successor$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$DALL-E 3 is OpenAI's AI image generator, now being retired in 2026 in favor of GPT Image models. See pricing, history, and what's replacing it.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$DALL-E is the name of a family of text-to-image AI models developed by OpenAI, the artificial intelligence research and deployment company founded in December 2015 by a group that included Sam Altman, Elon Musk, Greg Brockman, Ilya Sutskever, and others, and headquartered in San Francisco. The original DALL-E was announced in January 2021 as a research demonstration showing that a GPT-3-style transformer model, trained jointly on text and images, could generate plausible images from arbitrary text captions. DALL-E 2, a substantially higher-fidelity successor using a diffusion-based architecture, launched on April 6, 2022, and was rolled out gradually: a beta period opened to roughly one million waitlisted users starting July 20, 2022, the waitlist was removed entirely on September 28, 2022, and an API for developers followed in early November 2022. DALL-E 3 was released natively inside ChatGPT for ChatGPT Plus and Enterprise subscribers in October 2023, with API and 'Labs' platform access following in early November 2023; DALL-E 3 improved prompt-following accuracy substantially over DALL-E 2 and could render legible text within images far more reliably, and it was built with tighter integration into ChatGPT so users could iterate on prompts conversationally.

As of mid-2026, DALL-E 3 is in the process of being formally retired. OpenAI announced on November 14, 2025 that DALL-E 3 would be removed from the API on May 12, 2026, and Microsoft's Azure OpenAI Service had already retired its DALL-E 3 endpoint on March 4, 2026. Inside ChatGPT itself, OpenAI transitioned default image generation away from DALL-E 3 to its newer GPT Image model line (GPT Image 1, and later GPT Image 1.5) around December 2025, meaning most consumer-facing 'DALL-E' image generation inside ChatGPT today is actually powered by the GPT Image successor models rather than the DALL-E 3 model itself. This makes DALL-E, and specifically DALL-E 3, historically significant as the model that popularized mainstream AI image generation for millions of ChatGPT users, but increasingly a legacy brand as OpenAI consolidates its image generation roadmap under the GPT Image name, which is built on the same underlying multimodal architecture as GPT-4o-class models rather than DALL-E's earlier diffusion-based lineage.

Historically, DALL-E's pricing and access model evolved through several stages: DALL-E 2 initially used a credit-based system for free users before OpenAI simplified to per-image API pricing; DALL-E 3 was made available at no direct per-image cost to ChatGPT Plus ($20/month) and Enterprise subscribers as part of their subscription, with a limited number of free images available to users on ChatGPT's free tier (typically two to three images per day, subject to change), while API access to DALL-E 3 was billed per image, with standard 1024x1024 resolution priced at roughly $0.04 per image and higher-resolution or HD-quality outputs priced between roughly $0.08 and $0.12 per image. As DALL-E 3 sunsets, OpenAI's GPT Image models have become the pricing and product reference point going forward, with GPT Image 1.5 starting at roughly $0.03 per image for standard quality via the API, positioned as OpenAI's forward-looking, 'future-proof' image generation offering.

DALL-E's core differentiators, particularly at its 2022-2023 peak, were tight integration with ChatGPT's conversational interface (letting users refine an image through natural-language follow-up rather than re-writing a prompt from scratch), strong adherence to complex, multi-object prompts, and industry-leading in-image text rendering compared to contemporaries at the time. Its most direct competitors across its lifespan have included Midjourney (widely regarded as offering stronger raw aesthetic quality for artistic outputs), Stability AI's Stable Diffusion and its many fine-tuned variants (notably cheaper and self-hostable), Google's Imagen and Gemini-integrated image generation, Adobe Firefly (with a commercial-safe licensing angle for enterprise creative workflows), and the open-weight Flux model family from Black Forest Labs, which by 2026 was frequently cited as matching or exceeding DALL-E 3's quality at a lower API price point with better text rendering. Typical users of DALL-E have spanned casual ChatGPT users generating images conversationally, marketers and content creators producing quick visual assets, and developers building DALL-E into third-party applications via the API, though the latter group is now being pushed toward GPT Image models given DALL-E 3's scheduled API removal. Given the deprecation timeline, any team or developer still integrating against the DALL-E 3 API should treat it as a legacy integration and plan a migration to GPT Image 1 or GPT Image 1.5 to avoid a service disruption once OpenAI completes the retirement.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'c4134253-62ea-44f0-8d58-12d26946aac4';

